Minimum wage and individual worker productivity: Evidence from a large US retailer

Journal of Political Economy, Volume 130, No.9, September 2022:

by Desio Coviello, Erika Deserranno, Nicola Persico

20220809 12:20

Summary

Figure 4: Effects of a USD 1 increase in the minimum wage on the percent change in Y (Sales/Hrs) for low, medium, or high types workers for high/low monitoring coverage. Low Types are workers for whom the total pay per hour in month \(t-1\) is at minimum wage; Medium Type are workers for whom the total pay per hour in month \(t-1\) is between the minimum wage and 180% of minimum wage; High Type are workers for whom the total pay per hour in month \(t-1\) is above 180% of minimum wage. Monitoring coverage is measured as the ratio of supervisors to workers. Low coverage is an indicator for whether the store is in the bottom quartile of the monitoring coverage distribution. Vertical bars (solid for Low coverage, dashed otherwise) represent 95% confidence intervals.

  • Minimum wage increases worker productivity at the low end and the centre of the distribution (low types and medium types), if monitored.
  • If not monitored, worker productivity of low and medium types does not increase with MW.
  • A sample from a large US wide retailer.
  • State border discontinuity: Stores in county-pairs (centroids\(\leqslant 75\) km apart), with worker and county-pair FEs.
  • Workers are supplemented with a gap: MW - actual reward, if positive.
  • In theory, MW impacts on worker productivity are two: Efficiency wage (\(+\)) and reduced incentives (\(-\)).
  • MW increases the value of employment which induces worker efforts, while wage fixing prevents them.
  • A model is constructed to show the former is larger for low types under supervision. Low types face a greater probability of being fired, necessitating increased efforts.

Context

  • Company: Hires 10% of national department store employees, 2K stores in all 50 states.
  • February 2012 - June 2015: 70 MW increases (state 49, county/city 21).
  • Mean MW = 7.87, mean \(\Delta\)MW = .54.
  • 40K+ salespeople \(\rightarrow\) 10K salespeople in 200 stores in contiguous county-pair sample.
  • Mean pay = USD 1361/month, mean base pay = USD6.12/hour, mean variable pay = USD5.95/unit sales, mean salespeople/store = 16.64, mean turnover/store = 3.4% per month.
  • Wage: Mix of fixed wage and piece rate.
  • Fair Labor Standards Act: Fill gap = MW - actual wage.
  • 42% of workers received gap filling (MW adjustment) at least once in 4 weeks.
  • Empirical definition of low types: People who were paid MW in \(t-1\), or 4% of observations. (Time varying?) Medium types 72.4%, high types 23.7%.
  • A USD 1 increase in MW increases MW adjustment by USD .25/hour, increases variable pay by USD .44/hour. Shows an endogenous performance increase (Table 2).

Identification

Figure C2: Contiguous county pairs

Border discontinuity design (contiguous county-pair comparisons). Stores located in paired-counties whose centroids are less than 75km apart.

Figure 2: Event study presentation

\[\begin{align} Y_{ijpt}&=\alpha+\beta \text{MinW}_{jt}+X_{it}\zeta+\eta Z_{jt}+\delta_{i}+\phi_{pt}+\epsilon_{ijpt}.\tag{10}\\ Y_{ijpt} &= \beta_{0}+\beta_{1}\text{MinW}_{jt} +\beta_{2}\text{MediumType}_{ijt} +\beta_{3}\text{HighType}_{ijt}\\ &\hspace{2.25em}+\beta_{4}\text{MinW}_{jt}\cdot\text{MediumType}_{ijt} +\beta_{5}\text{MinW}_{jt}\cdot\text{HighType}_{ijt}\tag{11}\\ &\hspace{2.25em}+X_{it}\zeta+\eta Z_{jt}+\delta_{i}+\phi_{pt}+\epsilon_{ijpt}.\\ Y_{ijpt} &= \alpha+\sum_{m=-2}^{2}\beta^{3m}_{1}\text{MinW}_{j, t-3*m} +\gamma_{1}\text{MediumType}_{ijt} +\gamma_{2}\text{HighType}_{ijt}\\ &\hspace{2.25em}+ \sum_{m=-2}^{2}\beta^{3m}_{2}\text{MinW}_{j, t-3*m}\cdot\text{MediumType}_{ijt}\tag{12}\\ &\hspace{2.25em}+ \sum_{m=-2}^{2}\beta^{3m}_{3}\text{MinW}_{j, t-3*m}\cdot\text{HighType}_{ijt}\\ &\hspace{2.25em} +X_{it}\zeta+\eta Z_{jt}+\delta_{i}+\phi_{pt}+\epsilon_{ijpt}. \end{align}\]

Stacking our data (multiple use of a single observation): A county bordering \(n\) counties can appear \(n\) times.

No pre-trend.

Results

Core findings

See the figures at the top.

  • Increase in sales/hour: 22.6% (low), 8.2% (medium), 2.3% (high, statistically zero).
  • Mean increae in sales/hour: 4.5% or elasticity of .35.
  • No change in number of workers (Table 6) nor hours worked (Figure 7 or Table F6 shows increased hours for medium and high types wierd).

Robustness

No cross border movements.

  • Corr[\(\Delta\)MW, home-to-work distance of new hires] = small (Table E2).
  • Home-to-work distance of all workers do not differ across types.

Figure 5: Reduced turnovers for more low types

No worker selection through retention after MW changes.

  • Balanced panel shows similar results.
  • Bounds for selection bias is small relative to estimates.

Similar results: Alternative cutoff for types, alternative research design using state-level contiguity, alternative border band, unstacking, alternative controls.

Turnovers are reduced and tenure is extended for stores with more low types.

Nationally, store outputs increase but EBITDA (earnings before interest taxes depreciation and amortization) decreases (Table 8). Suggests output increase did not compensate for increased labour costs.

Figure F1: Proxying demand with parking lot occupancy

Demand channel (incidentally increased demand at the time of MW increase, or pass-through on prices which works against increased demand) does not affect the results: Parking lot satellite imagery shows high demand coincides with increased sales of high types. No spillovers: Number of employees as covariate does not change results.

No statistically detectable company response to MW: Allocation of low types to top departments, change hours/month, change ratios of part timers, change benefits/month.

A model

Set up and assumptions

Type \(x\)s effort \(e\) choice problem: \[ V^{E}(x)=\max_{\{e\in[0,1]\}}\;\; w(x, e)-c(x, e)+\frac{1}{1+r}\left[\pi(e)V^{E}(x)+\left\{1-\pi(e)\right\}V^{A}\right]. \]

  • Expected compensation \(w(x, e)=\mathbb{E}\left[\bar{w}\{Y(x, e)\}\right]\) with a stochastic output \(Y(x, e)\) and a fixed compensation scheme \(\bar{w}(Y)\).
  • Probability of employment continuation \(\pi(e)\).
  • Unemployment value \(V^{A}\).
  • Random output satisfies monotone likelihood ratio property (MLRP) in \(x, e\) \(\Rightarrow\) Increasing \(x, e\) produces stochastically larger output, or first-order stochastic dominance of output distribution \(F_{Y}\).

\(\eqref{eq2}\) shows to maxmise current net utility flow \(u(x, e)\) and discounted expected net employment value \(\frac{1}{1+r}\pi(e)V(x)\). Add \(\frac{r}{1+r}V^{E}(x)\) on both sides: \[ \begin{aligned} V^{E}+\frac{r}{1+r}V^{A} &= w-c+\frac{1}{1+r}\pi\left(V^{E}-V^{A}\right)+\left(\frac{1}{1+r}+\frac{r}{1+r}\right)V^{A},\\ \overbrace{V^{E}(x)-V^{A}}^{V(x)} &= \overbrace{w(x, e)-c(x, e)-\frac{r}{1+r}V^{A}}^{u(x, e)}+ \frac{1}{1+r}\pi(e)\overbrace{\left(V^{E}(x)-V^{A}\right)}^{V(x)}, \end{aligned} \] \[\begin{equation} V(x) = \max_{\{e\in[0,1]\}}\;\; u(x, e)+\frac{1}{1+r}\pi(e)V(x).\tag{2}\label{eq2} \end{equation}\]

\(u_{xe}\)>0, based on higher types have higher net marginal returns on efforts, is standard. Assumption 2 implies the problem \(\eqref{eq2}\) is strictly concave in \(e\) so there is an interior solution. No.2 of (#ref-ass3: Assumption 3) implies even maximum efforts \(e=1\) has a chance of receiving minimum wages with a positive probability. One also needs IRC that the effort set such that \(u(x, e)\)>0 is nonempty for all \(x\).

Assumption 1
\(u_{x}>0\), \(u_{xe}>0\), \(u_{ee}<0\).

Assumption 2
\(\pi(e)\) is weakly concave in \(e\).

Assumption 3
\(\bar{w}(\cdot)\) is strictly increasing in \(Y\). \(w_{M}(x, 1; M)>0\). \(|w_{eM}(x, e; M)|<\infty\).

Lemma 1
1. Existence and uniqueness of solution \(e^{*}(x)\).
2. \(e^{*}(x)\) is nondecreasing in \(x\), strictly increasing under the interior solution.
3. If \(\pi^{\prime}(e)\) is positive for all \(e\), then \(e^{*}(x)\) is an interior solution for all \(x\). FOC: \[\begin{equation} u_{e}(x, e)+\frac{1}{1+r}\pi'(e)V(x)=0. \tag{4}\label{foc} \end{equation}\]

Linking the model to empirical setting

Introducing minimum wages. \[ w(x, e; M)=\mathbb E\left[\max(M, \bar{w}\{Y(x, e)\})\right]. \] \(M\) is minimum wage level. Note \(w(x, e; M)\) is nondecreasing in all arguments.

Definition MMW
Type \(x\) is motivated by minimum wage (MMW) or low type if \(w(x, e; M)=M\) for all \(e\). MMW cannot increase wage with \(e\), or \(w_{e}=0\). MMWs only incentive to increase efforts is job security (efficiency wage concerns). Pure efficiency wage case where everyone is MMW type is inconsistent with data, so ignore this polar case.

Two cases that are nested:

  1. Pure pay for performance: \(\pi'(e)=0\) or no monitoring. Problem reduces to flow utility maximisation. Efforts come only from performance pay.
  2. Hybrid: P4P and efficiency wage: \(\pi'(e)>0\) and \(M\) is not too high. Low types motivated by efficiency wages only and high types motivated by both efficiency wage and performance pay.

Proposition 1 (Minimum wage effects on efforts)

Proof sketch:
1. FOC in \(\eqref{foc}\) is increasing in \(M\) for MMW because \(w=0\), \(c_{eM}=0\) and \(V_{M}(x; M)\)>0, so optimal effort level must go up when \(M\) increases to bring FOC back to zero.
2. As \(M\) increases, \(x\) that switches from \(e^{*}\uparrow\) to \(e^{*}\downarrow\) leads to a contradiction.
3. \(\bar{w}(Y)\) has an upperbound given \(Y\) is bounded from above, and for a large enough \(M\), expected wage \(w(x, e; M)=M\), so everyone becomes MMW. MMW: \(M\uparrow\) \(\sim\) \(e^{*}\uparrow\).
4. If \(\lim\limits_{x\rightarrow\infty} w_{M}(x, e; M)=0\), can show FOC stays zero with a change in \(M\), because \(V(x; M)\) is a fixed point and \(w_{M}=0\) for any \(e\).

  1. \(M\uparrow\) \(\sim\) \(e^{*}\uparrow\) for MMW (low types) under monitoring.
  2. Set of \(x\) such that \(M\uparrow\) \(\sim\) \(e^{*}\uparrow\) increases with \(M\).
  3. For a high enough \(M\), \(M\uparrow\) \(\sim\) \(e^{*}\uparrow\) for all \(x\).
  4. For \(x\) whose wage is unaffected by \(M\), or high types, \(M\uparrow\) \(\not\sim\) \(e^{*}\uparrow\).

Proposition 2 (Role of monitoring)

Proof sketch:
1. \(\eqref{eq2}\) gives \[ V(x, e; M)=\frac{1+r}{1+r-\pi(e)}u(x, e; M). \] By definition, \(Q(x, e; M)\equiv \ln V(x, e; M)\) attains its global maximum at \(e^{*}\). \[ Q_{e}(x, e; M)=\frac{d}{de}\ln u(x, e; M)+\left[-\frac{d}{de}\ln \{1+r-\pi(e)\}\right]. \] If the second term, elasticity of \(1+r-\pi(e)\) with respect to \(e\), gets large pointwise, \(Q_{e}\) function shifts up in \((Q_{e}, e)\) space, hence the maximiser \(e^{*}\) increases.
2. Can show \(w_{eM}(x, e; M)\)<0 at \(e^{*}(x; M)\) so \(e^{*}\) must decrease.
3. Envelope theorem gives derivative of maximum value function = derivative of Lagrangian at optimum. So, from \(\eqref{eq2}\): \[ \begin{aligned} V_{M}(x; M) = \left.u_{M}(x, e; M)\right|_{e=e^{*}(x; M)}+\frac{1}{1+r}\left.\pi(e)\right|_{e=e^{*}(x; M)}V_{M}(x; M),\\ = u_{M}\left\{x, e^{*}(x; M); M\right\}+\frac{1}{1+r}\pi\left\{e^{*}(x; M)\right\}V_{M}(x; M),\\ = \frac{1+r}{1+r-\pi\left\{e^{*}(x; M)\right\}}u_{M}\left\{x, e^{*}(x; M); M\right\}. \end{aligned} \] Implict function theorem gives \(de=\left\{u_{eM}+\frac{\pi^{\prime}(e)}{1+r}V_{M}(x; M)\right\}dM\), or \[ \frac{de}{dM}=u_{eM}+\frac{\pi^{\prime}(e)}{1+r}V_{M}(x; M)\equiv Q_{eM}(x, e; M). \] Plug \(V_{M}(x; M)\) into the above: \[\begin{equation} \left.Q_{eM}(x, e; M)\right|_{e=e^{*}(x; M)}= u_{eM}(x, e; M)\\ \hspace{1em}+\left.\frac{\pi^{\prime}(e)}{1+r-\pi(e)}u_{M}(x, e; M)\right|_{e=e^{*}(x; M)}\\ \geq \min_{\eta} w_{eM}(x, \eta; M)+\left.\frac{\pi^{\prime}(e)}{1+r-\pi(e)}\right|_{e=e^{*}(x; M)}w_{M}(x, 1; M). \tag{20}\label{eq20} \end{equation}\] If \(Q_{eM}(x, e; M)\) is positive at \(e^{*}(x; M)\), then \(\frac{de}{dM}\)>0. This is shown by finiteness of \(u_{eM}(x, e; M)=w_{eM}(x, e; M)\) and \(u_{M}(x, 1; M)=w_{M}(x, 1; M)\)>0 under a large enough \(\pi^{\prime}(e)\) so the 2nd term dominates.

  1. Monitoring intensity \(-\frac{d}{de}\ln \{1+r-\pi(e)\} \uparrow\) \(\sim\) \(e^{*}\uparrow\) for all \(x\).
  2. If \(\pi'(e)=0\), \(e^{*}=0\) for MMW and \(M\uparrow\) \(\sim\) \(e^{*}\downarrow\) for non MMW.
  3. Under sufficiently intense monitoring \(\pi'(e)\), \(M\uparrow\) \(\sim\) \(e^{*}\uparrow\) for all \(x\).

Prop 2.2 says: Under no monitoring, as MW increases, MMW do not change efforts while high types reduce them.
Prop 2.3 says: Under close monitoring, as MW increases, all types increase efforts.

Proposition 3 (Minimum wage effects on turnover)
\(M\uparrow\) \(\sim\) worker inflow \(\lambda\downarrow\)

Lemma 2 (Minimum wage effects on profits)
\(M\uparrow\) cannot increase nationwide profits.
